=1> Okay, so not exactly manga, but I just finished reading the first three books last night (forget the name of the first one...? then UNTIL THE END OF THE EARTH, and then PROUD AMERICANS), and I'm desperate to talk to someone...!<br>
<br>
Christ, did I enjoy the first one! The artwork was amazing, the characters interesting and unusual, the storyline involving and detailed - and complex! Well-written, too...<br>
But sadly, it went downhill.... not quite sure what happened, but I was left at the end of PROUD AMERICANS thinking the author was a giant arse, and nothing would please me more than giving him a large facial slap. I guess to begin with the violence was shocking and scary, the character's actions had repercussions (like cops trying to arrest them), and the plot was interesting...<br>
but I guess anal rape just isn't funny. Especially when, after a good deal of story line, the reader has had such a giant amount of violence, blood, explosions and other nastiness shoved down their throat and are feeling utterly desensitised, they just don't care after a while. I found it, frankly, offensive that the characters (talkin' the main characters here - Jesse, Tulip and Cassidy) spend long amounts of time attempting to morally justify the large amounts of murder they commit during the story (ie - in order to protect my friend - because if you're prepared to abandon your friends &quot;you may as well go join the @#%$ squad&quot;). I don't find their reasoning convincing. How is it okay for Jesse to execute endless faceless grunts (I mean, for crying out loud, that whole word of god &quot;go @#%$ yourself&quot; thing in the first book!) and yet he brings down almighty hell when he finds, for example, Jesus D'Sade making a porn movie involving a child.<br>
Cassidy seems to only be a vampire in order for him to be regularly peppered with holes, have limbs blown off, bleed copiously on the floor, and yet not die. Jesse is disappointingly sexist, and has expressed some deeply depressing racist views (eg, his views on the French, while Tulip and himself eat in a French restaurant in Paris) and even more depressing patriotism is present in every character. Patriotism, generally, I object to - I'm not one. I think it's a little silly declaring loyalty to a country just because you were born there. Coincidence.<br>
And even Cassidy bangs on about how amazing America is. He's fuckin' Irish!!! okay, he moved to America, &quot;land of opportunity&quot;, but the author spends large amounts of time criticising other countries and cultures, and yet fails to see the flaws in his own? Stupidity!<br>
<br>
okay, this is quickly getting huge. Better wrap it up. What else annoyed me...?<br>
erm.<br>
1 - Jesse being self-righteous and as arrogant as they come. Just because he's the &quot;hero&quot; doesn't make him automatically right. I find him a bit of a sexist tosser, to be honest.<br>
2 - Tulip's the only female character of any note whatsoever (okay, apart from Gran'ma) - and she's written out of the biggest (and thus most dangerous) story line so far (Starr and the Grail in the 3rd book) because of some whingeing over-emphasised problem Jesse seems to have with a woman watching his back! This sexist attitude is backed up by his little talks with John Wayne - remember about how a partner and a woman are different things? You can't have a partner who's a woman, and vice versa?  rrr. Despite the fact that she saves Jesse's life several times and is proven brilliant with a gun.<br>
I mean, partnership is the theme of the entire third book, PROUD AMERICANS - obvious from the twin seperate story lines of Jesse's dad in 'Nam (dull, dull, dull) and Cassidy's little (dull) backstory. Cassidy and Jesse are the partners. Tulip gets written out... anyway, she can't be a partner, she's a woman, remember???<br>
<br>
might come back and add to this later, mind's gone blank and it's my lunch hour... but yeah, any thoughts?? I'm interested to hear 'em, even if you think me personal ideas are only worthy of unreasonable amounts of roaring flame.<br>
<br>
<br>
and, no. that's not an excuse to flame me!!!<br>
